# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: opensearch
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] Lucene has been ported to other programming languages including Object Pascal, Perl, C#, C++, Python, Ruby and PHP.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] Doug Cutting originally wrote Lucene in 1999.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] He had previously written two while at Xerox PARC, one at Apple, and a fourth at Excite.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] It was initially available for download from its home at the SourceForge web site.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] It joined the Apache Software Foundation's Jakarta family of open-source Java products in September 2001 and became its own top-level Apache project in February 2005.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] The name Lucene is Doug Cutting's wife's middle name and her maternal grandmother's first name.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] Lucene formerly included a number of sub-projects, such as Lucene.NET, Mahout, Tika and Nutch.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] These three are now independent top-level projects.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] In March 2010, the Apache Solr search server joined as a Lucene sub-project, merging the developer communities.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] Version 4.0 was released on October 12, 2012.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] In March 2021, Lucene changed its logo, and Apache Solr became a top level Apache project again, independent from Lucene.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] While suitable for any application that requires full text indexing and searching capability, Lucene is recognized for its utility in the implementation of Internet search engines and local, single-site searching.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] Lucene includes a feature to perform a fuzzy search based on edit distance.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] Lucene has also been used to implement recommendation systems.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] For example, Lucene's 'MoreLikeThis' Class can generate recommendations for similar documents.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] In contrast, citation-based document similarity measures tended to be more suitable for recommending more broadly related documents, meaning citation-based approaches may be more suitable for generating serendipitous recommendations, as long as documents to be recommended contain in-text citations.
[src:opensearch/apache-lucene] Lucene itself is just an indexing and search library and does not contain crawling and HTML parsing functionality.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is distributed and uses JSON documents stored in indices divided into shards, each of which may have replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] It supports full-text search, faceted search, real-time search, and multitenancy.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] The software is developed alongside Logstash, Kibana, and Beats as part of the Elastic Stack (formerly the ELK Stack).
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Shay Banon created the precursor to Elasticsearch, called Compass, in 2004.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Developing a third version of Compass, he concluded that a full rewrite was necessary to build a scalable, distributed search solution using JSON over HTTP as a common interface.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] He released the first version of Elasticsearch in February 2010.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Elastic NV was founded in 2012 to provide commercial services and products around Elasticsearch and related software.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] In June 2014, the company raised $70 million in a Series C funding round led by New Enterprise Associates, with additional funding from Benchmark Capital and Index Ventures, bringing total funding to $104 million.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] In March 2015, the company changed its name from *Elasticsearch* to *Elastic* and, through the acquisition of Found, launched a managed cloud offering later known as Elastic Cloud.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] In November 2017, Elastic acquired the search startup Swiftype, whose technology became the basis for Elastic App Search and Elastic Site Search.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Elastic also formed partnerships with Google to offer Elastic Cloud on Google Cloud Platform and with Alibaba to offer Elasticsearch and Kibana on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] In June 2018, Elastic filed for an initial public offering with an estimated valuation of between $1.5 and $3 billion.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] On 5 October 2018, Elastic was listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] In January 2021, Elastic announced that starting with version 7.11, Elasticsearch and Kibana would be relicensed from Apache License 2.0 to a dual license under the Server Side Public License and the Elastic License, neither of which is recognised as an open-source license.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Elastic stated the change was a response to Amazon Web Services (AWS) offering Elasticsearch and Kibana as a service without what Elastic described as adequate collaboration.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Critics of the change noted that Elastic had previously promised never to alter the Apache 2.0 licensing of Elasticsearch, Kibana, Beats, and Logstash, and predicted the move would damage the ecosystem.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] AWS responded by announcing a fork of the projects to continue development under Apache License 2.0.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Other members of the Elasticsearch ecosystem, including Logz.io, CrateDB, and Aiven, also committed to supporting a fork.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Due to potential trademark conflicts with the name "Elasticsearch", AWS rebranded their fork as OpenSearch in April 2021.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] In August 2024, Elastic added the GNU Affero General Public License as a third licensing option for Elasticsearch starting with version 8.16.0.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] This made the software available under a free and open-source license once again alongside the two source-available options.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is built on Apache Lucene and exposes Lucene's capabilities through a JSON and Java API.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Documents are stored in indices, which are divided into primary shards; each shard may have zero or more replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Routing and rebalancing are handled automatically.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Once an index has been created, the number of primary shards cannot be changed.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] The engine supports faceted search and percolation, a form of prospective search in which stored queries are matched against incoming documents rather than the reverse.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] A gateway module handles long-term index persistence, allowing an index to be recovered after a node failure.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Real-time GET requests make Elasticsearch usable as a NoSQL datastore, though it does not support distributed transactions.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] In May 2019, Elastic made the core security features of the Elastic Stack available without charge, including TLS for encrypted communications, file and native realm authentication, and role-based access control for cluster APIs and indices.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] The corresponding source code is available under the Elastic License.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch also offers SIEM and machine learning capabilities as part of its commercial offerings.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Official client libraries are maintained for Java, C# (.NET), PHP, Python, and Ruby, among others.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is developed alongside Logstash (a data collection and log-parsing engine), Kibana (an analytics and visualisation platform), and Beats (lightweight data shippers).
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] The four products are designed for use together as the Elastic Stack.
[src:opensearch/elasticsearch] The combination was previously known as the ELK Stack, an initialism for "Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana".
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] OpenSearch is a distributed search and analytics engine that supports various use cases, from implementing a search box on a website to analyzing security data for threat detection.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] The term *distributed* means that you can run OpenSearch on multiple computers.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] *Search and analytics* means that you can search and analyze your data once you ingest it into OpenSearch.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] No matter your type of data, you can store and analyze it using OpenSearch.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Watch this video to learn key OpenSearch concepts and understand how OpenSearch organizes data and ranks search results.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] A *document* is a unit that stores information (text or structured data).
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] In OpenSearch, documents are stored in JSON format.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] For example, in a school database, a document might represent one student and contain the following data.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] You’ll learn about how document IDs are assigned in Indexing documents.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] An *index* is a collection of documents.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] For example, in a school database, an index might contain all students in the school.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] OpenSearch is designed to be a distributed search engine, meaning that it can run on one or more *nodes*—servers that store your data and process search requests.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] An OpenSearch *cluster* is a collection of nodes.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] You can run OpenSearch locally on a laptop—its system requirements are minimal—but you can also scale a single cluster to hundreds of powerful machines in a data center.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] In a single-node cluster, such as one deployed on a laptop, one machine has to perform every task: manage the state of the cluster, index and search data, and perform any preprocessing of data prior to indexing it.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] As a cluster grows, however, you can subdivide responsibilities.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Nodes with fast disks and plenty of RAM might perform well when indexing and searching data, whereas a node with plenty of CPU power and a tiny disk could manage cluster state.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] In each cluster, there is an elected *cluster manager* node, which orchestrates cluster-level operations, such as creating an index.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Nodes communicate with each other, so if your request is routed to a node, that node sends requests to other nodes, gathers the nodes’ responses, and returns the final response.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] For more information about other node types, see Cluster formation.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] OpenSearch splits indexes into *shards*.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Each shard stores a subset of all documents in an index, as shown in the following image.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Shards are used for even distribution across nodes in a cluster.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] For example, a 400 GB index might be too large for any single node in your cluster to handle, but split into 10 shards of 40 GB each, OpenSearch can distribute the shards across 10 nodes and manage each shard individually.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Consider a cluster with 2 indexes: index 1 and index 2.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Index 1 is split into 2 shards, and index 2 is split into 4 shards.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] The shards are distributed across nodes 1 and 2, as shown in the following image.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Despite being one piece of an OpenSearch index, each shard is actually a full Lucene index.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] This detail is important because each instance of Lucene is a running process that consumes CPU and memory.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Splitting a 400 GB index into 1,000 shards, for example, would unnecessarily strain your cluster.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] A good rule of thumb is to limit shard size to 10–50 GB.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Each shard is either a *primary shard* (or, simply, *primary*)—the original copy of the data—or a *replica shard* (or, simply, *replica*)—a copy of a primary shard.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] By default, OpenSearch creates a replica shard for each primary shard.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Thus, if you split your index into 10 shards, OpenSearch creates 10 replica shards.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] For example, consider the cluster described in the previous section.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] If you add 1 replica for each shard of each index in the cluster, your cluster will contain a total of 2 primary shards and 2 replica shards for index 1 and 4 primary shards and 4 replica shards for index 2, as shown in the following image.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] These replica shards act as backups in the event of a node failure—OpenSearch distributes replica shards to different nodes than their corresponding primary shards—but they also improve the speed at which the cluster processes search requests.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] You might specify more than one replica per index for a search-heavy workload.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] An OpenSearch index uses a data structure called an *inverted index*.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] An inverted index maps words to the documents in which they occur.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] In addition to the document ID, OpenSearch stores the position of the word within the document for running phrase queries, where words must appear next to each other.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] When you search for a document, OpenSearch matches the words in the query to the words in the documents.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] For example, if you search the index described in the previous section for the word `beauty`, OpenSearch will return documents 1 and 2.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Each document is assigned a *relevance score* that tells you how well the document matched the query.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] Individual words in a search query are called search *terms*.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] A search term that occurs in more documents will tend to be scored lower.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] A query for the terms `blue` and `axolotl` should prefer documents that contain `axolotl` over the likely more common word `blue`.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] This is the *inverse document frequency* component of the score.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] A match on a longer document should tend to be scored lower than a match on a shorter document.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] A document that contains a full dictionary would match on any word but is not very relevant to any particular word.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] This corresponds to the *length normalization* component of the score.
[src:opensearch/getting-started-intro] OpenSearch uses the BM25 ranking algorithm to calculate document relevance scores and then returns the results sorted by relevance.
[src:opensearch/latest-about] This section contains documentation for OpenSearch and OpenSearch Dashboards.
[src:opensearch/latest-about] OpenSearch is supported by the OpenSearch Software Foundation.
[src:opensearch/latest-about] All components are available under the Apache License, Version 2.0 on GitHub.
[src:opensearch/latest-about] The project welcomes GitHub issues, bug fixes, features, plugins, documentation—anything at all.
[src:opensearch/latest-about] OpenSearch includes certain Apache-licensed Elasticsearch code from Elasticsearch B.V. and other source code.
[src:opensearch/latest-about] Elasticsearch B.V. is not the source of that other source code.
[src:opensearch/latest-about] ELASTICSEARCH is a registered trademark of Elasticsearch B.V.
[src:opensearch/latest] Build your OpenSearch solution using core tooling and visualizations.
[src:opensearch/latest] Use vector database capabilities for more relevant search results.
[src:opensearch/latest] Power your applications with machine learning model integration.
[src:opensearch/latest] Explore and visualize your data using interactive dashboards.
[src:opensearch/latest] Filter, mutate, and sample your data for ingestion into OpenSearch.
[src:opensearch/latest] Interact with OpenSearch from your application using language APIs.
[src:opensearch/latest] Measure OpenSearch cluster performance metrics.
[src:opensearch/latest] Simplify your upgrade or migration to OpenSearch.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] As of 2025, the project had surpassed one billion software downloads.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] AWS previously reported that OpenSearch had "tens of thousands" of customers, while Elastic claimed to have over 20,000 subscribers.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] The project was created in 2021 by Amazon Web Services as a fork of Elasticsearch and Kibana after Elastic NV changed the license of new versions of this software away from the open-source Apache License in favour of the Server Side Public License (SSPL).
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Amazon would hold sole ownership status and write access to the source code repositories, but invited pull requests from anyone.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Other companies such as Logz.io, CrateDB, Red Hat and others announced an interest in building or joining a community to continue using and maintaining this open-source software.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] On September 16, 2024, the Linux Foundation and Amazon Web Services announced the creation of the OpenSearch Software Foundation.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Ownership of OpenSearch software was transferred from Amazon to the OpenSearch Software Foundation (OSSF), which is organized as an open technical project within the Linux Foundation.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] In September 2024, Elastic added the AGPLv3 license as an option alongside SSPL and the Elastic License for the core of Elasticsearch, though binary releases and higher-tier features remained under the Elastic License 2.0.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] OpenSearch 3.0, the project's first major version release in three years, was released in April 2025 alongside an upgrade to Apache Lucene 10.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] The release introduced significant performance improvements, including up to 25% faster range queries and 2.5× faster concurrent k-NN search.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] It also included experimental support for gRPC transport and GPU-accelerated vector indexing, a new Java agent-based security framework replacing the Java Security Manager, and pull-based ingestion from streaming sources such as Apache Kafka.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Subsequent 3.x minor releases continued adding capabilities.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] OpenSearch 3.1 made GPU-accelerated index builds generally available and introduced semantic field support and star-tree indexes for aggregation acceleration of up to 100×.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] OpenSearch 3.3 delivered 11× faster performance compared to OpenSearch 1.3 and expanded gRPC transport across major query types.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] OpenSearch 3.4 added a no-code agentic search user experience with Model Context Protocol (MCP) integration.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] OpenSearch 3.5, released in February 2026, added agentic conversation memory, hook-based context management for LLM token optimization, and expanded Prometheus support for observability workloads.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] OpenSearch is a Lucene-based search engine that started as a fork of version 7.10.2 of the Elasticsearch service.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] It has Elastic NV trademarks and telemetry removed.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] It is licensed under the Apache License, version 2, without a Contributor License Agreement.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Since version 3.0, OpenSearch is based on Apache Lucene 10.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] In addition to full-text search, OpenSearch supports vector search through multiple engines including Lucene, FAISS and nmslib, with support for vectors of up to 16,000 dimensions.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] This makes it suitable as a vector database for use cases such as semantic search and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] OpenSearch Dashboards started as a fork of version 7.10.2 of Elastic's Kibana software, and is also under the Apache License, version 2.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] The OpenSearch Kubernetes Operator is an open-source operator for managing OpenSearch clusters on Kubernetes.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Version 3.0, released in January 2026, introduced quorum-safe rolling restarts, multi-namespace and multi-tenant support, TLS certificate hot reloading, and support for OpenSearch 3.0 features including gRPC.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] OpenSearch can be deployed as a self-managed cluster, via the managed Amazon OpenSearch Service, or through other managed providers such as Aiven and Instaclustr.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Third-party enterprise distributions also exist, such as BDB OpenSearch Enterprise by BigData Boutique, which provides long-term support (LTS) versions, security patches, hardened configurations, and enterprise support for self-managed deployments.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Core features such as LDAP and Active Directory integration, role-based access control, and encryption are included in OpenSearch's open-source distribution at no cost, unlike Elasticsearch where some of these features require a paid license.
[src:opensearch/opensearch-software] Community-backed solutions built on OpenSearch include Wazuh, an open-source XDR and SIEM platform.
